antage compared to ground launch.  The shuttle and Apollo launch pads dump something like 100,000 gallons of water below the pad during launch to suppress the shockwave and flame etc.  A Sea Dragon could be towed out on a huge barge, erected, fueled and launched.  The barge could partially flood itself to mimic the ground launch water suppression system... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 230<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/1/02 1:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=527.topic&index=49>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: a technical problem.</span><hr size=1> Re-read the articles about it.<br>
 No barge. It floats right in the water, and launches right out of it.<br>
<br>
 It's all worked out. If Aerojet general and the USAF &amp; NASA were satisfied, then I doubt there's much we here will be able to add to it.<br>
 The Navy launches ICBMs, ASW missiles, and cruise missiles directly from the water all the time. They depend on it to win battles, not to make a buck, so they take it seriously.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  The 32-meter (105-foot)-tall solid propellant HYDRA-1 was launched in March 1960, directly out of the ocean off Point Mugu, California. The Navy conducted approximately 60 launches of rocket simulators and actual rockets over the course of the project... HYDRA validated the concept of launching directly from the sea, with the rocket's initial exhaust gasses being expelled directly into water.<br>
...<br>
(Sea Dragon) was to be fueled with RP-1 in a dry dock, then towed horizontally to the launch point. Upon its arrival, propellant transport ships would have loaded the vehicle with cryogenic propellants, and technicians would have flooded a ballast device to position the booster vertically. The booster would jettison the ballast at lift-off.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
