<br>
 The question about blast plume deflection underwater also brings up a few things not covered by the articles we've seen on it, and  difference between a Trident &amp; a Sea Dragon: size of the plume; the launch pads at KSC were built for Saturn-V and the Space Shuttle, and that's quite a bit bigger than a Tomahawk, so maybe it's only bigger rockets that need sound suppression. OTOH, the sound supression is stated to protect the tail feathers of the orbiter plane, which isn't a consideration on the Sea Dragon.<br>
 I'll bet that firing a rocket underwater makes a cavity in the water, so that lower density around the rocket is more of a problem than overpressures. We're not worried about the flames staying around to hit the rocket itself -they're escaping at high exhaust velocity. All the stuff at KSC is to protect things around the launch pad, not the rocket itself.<br>
The rocket just rides up out and away from all of it. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0> at: 10/3/02 10:47:12 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=discovery1>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 70<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/1/02 8:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=527.topic&index=52>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: a technical problem.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://astronautix.com/graphics/s/seadrag1.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
